286
00:26:33.800 --> 00:26:35.593 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:10.00% 
[over megaphone]
Please stop killing the whales.

287
00:26:38.138 --> 00:26:40.473 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
[Attenborough] <i>Animals</i>
<i>that had been viewed</i>

288
00:26:40.557 --> 00:26:43.768 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>as little more than</i>
<i>a source of oil and meat</i>

289
00:26:43.852 --> 00:26:46.521 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
<i>became personalities.</i>

290
00:26:49.024 --> 00:26:51.526 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
[protester over megaphone] We are men
and women, and we speak for children,

291
00:26:52.277 --> 00:26:56.489 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
and we're all saying,
"Please stop killing the whales."

292
00:26:58.533 --> 00:27:02.871 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
We have pursued animals to extinction
many times in our history,

293
00:27:03.747 --> 00:27:08.209 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
but now that it was visible,
it was no longer acceptable.

294
00:27:16.176 --> 00:27:20.680 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>The killing of whales</i>
<i>turned from a harvest to a crime.</i>

295
00:27:22.599 --> 00:27:26.144 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>A powerful shared conscience</i>
<i>had suddenly appeared.</i>

296
00:27:27.145 --> 00:27:30.690 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
Nobody wanted animals to become extinct.

297
00:27:32.150 --> 00:27:35.028 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
People were coming to care
for the natural world...

298
00:27:36.029 --> 00:27:39.657 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>as they were made aware</i>
<i>of the natural world.</i>

299
00:27:42.702 --> 00:27:47.290 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
And we now had the means to make
people across the world aware.

300
00:27:47.957 --> 00:27:49.959 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
[theme music playing]

301
00:27:54.923 --> 00:28:00.720 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
[Attenborough] <i>By the time</i> Life on Earth
<i>aired in 1979, I had entered my 50s.</i>

302
00:28:01.262 --> 00:28:04.349 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>There were twice the number</i>
<i>of people on the planet</i>

303
00:28:04.432 --> 00:28:06.684 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
<i>as there were when I was born.</i>

304
00:28:08.520 --> 00:28:14.692 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
You and I belong to the most widespread
and dominant species of animal on earth.

305
00:28:14.776 --> 00:28:17.862 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>We're certainly the most numerous</i>
<i>large animal.</i>

306
00:28:17.946 --> 00:28:22.200 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>There are something like</i>
<i>4,000 million of us today,</i>

307
00:28:22.283 --> 00:28:26.121 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
and we've reached this position
with meteoric speed.

308
00:28:26.788 --> 00:28:30.542 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
It's all happened
within the last 2,000 years or so.

309
00:28:30.625 --> 00:28:35.004 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
We seem to have broken loose
from the restrictions

310
00:28:35.088 --> 00:28:39.008 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
that have governed the activities
and numbers of other animals.

311
00:28:46.808 --> 00:28:48.560 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
[Attenborough] <i>We had broken loose.</i>

312
00:28:49.519 --> 00:28:53.189 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>We were apart</i>
<i>from the rest of life on earth,</i>

313
00:28:54.691 --> 00:28:57.193 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
<i>living a different kind of life.</i>

314
00:29:00.989 --> 00:29:03.783 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
<i>Our predators had been eliminated.</i>

315
00:29:06.453 --> 00:29:09.289 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
<i>Most of our diseases were under control.</i>

316
00:29:11.207 --> 00:29:14.753 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>We had worked out</i>
<i>how to produce food to order.</i>

317
00:29:17.130 --> 00:29:20.383 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
There was nothing left to restrict us.

318
00:29:21.176 --> 00:29:23.136 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
Nothing to stop us.

319
00:29:24.387 --> 00:29:26.431 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
Unless we stopped ourselves...

320
00:29:27.557 --> 00:29:32.187 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>we would keep consuming the earth</i>
<i>until we had used it up.</i>

321
00:29:35.106 --> 00:29:38.693 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
Saving individual species
or even groups of species

322
00:29:38.777 --> 00:29:40.528 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
would not be enough.

323
00:29:40.612 --> 00:29:43.948 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
Whole habitats would soon
start to disappear.

324
00:30:12.060 --> 00:30:18.107 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:10.00% 
<i>I first witnessed the destruction</i>
<i>of an entire habitat in Southeast Asia.</i>

325
00:30:19.025 --> 00:30:24.197 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>In the 1950s, Borneo was three-quarters</i>
<i>covered with rainforest.</i>

326
00:30:24.781 --> 00:30:26.908 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
[young Attenborough] <i>We heard</i>
<i>a crashing in the branches ahead.</i>

327
00:30:28.243 --> 00:30:30.912 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
<i>And there, only a few yards away,</i>

328
00:30:30.995 --> 00:30:35.875 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>we spotted a great furry red form</i>
<i>swaying in the trees.</i>

329
00:30:37.001 --> 00:30:38.169 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
<i>The orangutan.</i>

330
00:30:41.840 --> 00:30:43.341 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
[Attenborough] <i>By the end of the century,</i>

331
00:30:43.424 --> 00:30:47.595 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>Borneo's rainforest</i>
<i>had been reduced by half.</i>

332
00:30:53.643 --> 00:30:57.313 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>Rainforests are particularly</i>
<i>precious habitats.</i>

333
00:30:58.147 --> 00:30:59.399 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
[birds chirping]

334
00:30:59.482 --> 00:31:03.069 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>More than half of the species</i>
<i>on land live here.</i>

335
00:31:07.824 --> 00:31:12.745 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>They're places in which</i>
<i>evolution's talent for design soars.</i>

336
00:31:27.510 --> 00:31:29.637 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
[birds squawking]

337
00:31:37.061 --> 00:31:40.273 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
[clicking]

338
00:31:57.832 --> 00:32:03.379 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>Many of the millions of species</i>
<i>in the forest exist in small numbers.</i>

339
00:32:06.007 --> 00:32:09.344 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
<i>Every one has a critical role to play.</i>

340
00:32:14.390 --> 00:32:18.436 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>Orangutan mothers have to spend</i>
<i>ten years with their young,</i>

341
00:32:18.519 --> 00:32:22.315 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>teaching them which fruits</i>
<i>are worth eating.</i>

342
00:32:25.652 --> 00:32:27.070 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
<i>Without this training,</i>

343
00:32:27.153 --> 00:32:30.907 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>they would not complete their role</i>
<i>in dispersing seeds.</i>

344
00:32:32.367 --> 00:32:36.829 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>The future generations</i>
<i>of many tree species would be at risk.</i>

345
00:32:37.789 --> 00:32:42.335 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>And tree diversity is the key</i>
<i>to a rainforest.</i>

346
00:32:42.418 --> 00:32:46.005 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
[birds chirping]

347
00:32:46.089 --> 00:32:49.050 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>In a single small patch</i>
<i>of tropical rainforest,</i>

348
00:32:49.133 --> 00:32:52.345 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>there could be</i>
<i>700 different species of tree,</i>

349
00:32:52.428 --> 00:32:56.099 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>as many as there are</i>
<i>in the whole of North America.</i>

350
00:32:57.058 --> 00:33:03.523 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>And yet, this is what we've been</i>
<i>turning this dizzying diversity into.</i>

351
00:33:05.024 --> 00:33:08.069 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
<i>A monoculture of oil palm.</i>

352
00:33:11.614 --> 00:33:15.827 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
<i>A habitat that is dead in comparison.</i>

353
00:33:19.455 --> 00:33:23.960 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
And you see this curtain of green
with occasionally birds in it,

354
00:33:25.420 --> 00:33:27.839 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
and you think it's perhaps okay.

355
00:33:27.922 --> 00:33:29.340 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
But if you get in a helicopter,

356
00:33:29.424 --> 00:33:32.760 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
you see that
that is a strip about half a mile wide.

357
00:33:33.594 --> 00:33:35.221 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
And beyond that strip,

358
00:33:35.304 --> 00:33:40.560 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>there is nothing but regimented rows</i>
<i>of oil palms.</i>

359
00:33:49.652 --> 00:33:53.531 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>There is a double incentive</i>
<i>to cut down forests.</i>

360
00:33:55.491 --> 00:33:57.243 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
<i>People benefit from the timber...</i>

361
00:33:57.827 --> 00:34:02.123 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>and then benefit again from</i>
<i>farming the land that's left behind.</i>

362
00:34:03.249 --> 00:34:05.585 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
[chainsaw revs]

363
00:34:15.845 --> 00:34:21.476 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>Which is why we've cut down</i>
<i>three trillion trees across the world.</i>

364
00:34:21.559 --> 00:34:25.980 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>Half of the world's rainforests</i>
<i>have already been cleared.</i>

365
00:34:35.656 --> 00:34:37.241 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
<i>What we see happening today</i>

366
00:34:37.325 --> 00:34:42.371 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>is just the latest chapter</i>
<i>in a global process spanning millennia.</i>

367
00:34:48.753 --> 00:34:53.716 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>The deforestation of Borneo</i>
<i>has reduced the population of orangutan</i>

368
00:34:53.800 --> 00:34:59.180 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>by two-thirds since I first saw one</i>
<i>just over 60 years ago.</i>

369
00:35:06.437 --> 00:35:09.190 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
We can't cut down rainforests forever,

370
00:35:09.273 --> 00:35:13.945 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
and anything that we can't do forever is
by definition unsustainable.

371
00:35:15.113 --> 00:35:18.074 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
<i>If we do things that are unsustainable,</i>

372
00:35:18.157 --> 00:35:24.205 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>the damage accumulates ultimately to</i>
<i>a point where the whole system collapses.</i>

373
00:35:25.665 --> 00:35:29.585 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
No ecosystem,
no matter how big, is secure.

374
00:35:32.046 --> 00:35:35.216 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
<i>Even one as vast as the ocean.</i>

375
00:35:39.971 --> 00:35:44.559 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>This habitat was the subject</i>
<i>of the series</i> The Blue Planet,

376
00:35:44.642 --> 00:35:47.270 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
<i>which we were filming in the late '90s.</i>

377
00:36:01.200 --> 00:36:06.664 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
It was... an astonishing vision
of a completely unknown world,

378
00:36:06.747 --> 00:36:10.877 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
a world that had existed
since the beginning of time.

379
00:36:18.968 --> 00:36:22.388 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
All sorts of things that you had no idea
had ever existed,

380
00:36:22.471 --> 00:36:26.767 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
all in a multitude of colors,
all unbelievably beautiful.

381
00:36:30.771 --> 00:36:35.568 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>And all of them completely undisturbed</i>
<i>by your presence.</i>

382
00:36:43.784 --> 00:36:47.872 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>For much of its expanse,</i>
<i>the ocean is largely empty.</i>

383
00:36:49.790 --> 00:36:53.127 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
<i>But in certain places, there are hot spots</i>

384
00:36:53.211 --> 00:36:55.922 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>where currents bring nutrients</i>
<i>to the surface</i>

385
00:36:56.005 --> 00:36:59.258 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
<i>and trigger an explosion of life.</i>

386
00:37:05.097 --> 00:37:09.101 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>In such places,</i>
<i>huge shoals of fish gather.</i>

387
00:37:17.276 --> 00:37:19.779 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
<i>The problem is that our fishing fleets</i>

388
00:37:19.862 --> 00:37:24.116 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>are just as good at finding</i>
<i>those hot spots as are the fish.</i>

389
00:37:25.993 --> 00:37:31.457 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>When they do, they're able to gather</i>
<i>the concentrated shoals with ease.</i>

390
00:37:35.461 --> 00:37:38.756 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
<i>It was only in the '50s that large fleets</i>

391
00:37:38.839 --> 00:37:42.301 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>first ventured out</i>
<i>into international waters...</i>

392
00:37:43.177 --> 00:37:46.806 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>to reap the open ocean harvest</i>
<i>across the globe.</i>

393
00:37:49.058 --> 00:37:53.896 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>Yet, they've removed</i>
<i>90% of the large fish in the sea.</i>

394
00:38:01.654 --> 00:38:05.199 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>At first, they caught</i>
<i>plenty of fish in their nets.</i>

395
00:38:06.450 --> 00:38:09.078 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
<i>But within only a few years,</i>

396
00:38:09.161 --> 00:38:13.457 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:79.33% 
<i>the nets across the globe</i>
<i>were coming in empty.</i>

397
00:38:15.126 --> 00:38:17.962 position:50.00%,middle align:middle size:80.00% line:84.67% 
